# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: christofides-tsp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] In computer science and operations research, **approximation algorithms** are efficient algorithms that find approximate solutions to optimization problems (in particular NP-hard problems) with provable guarantees on the distance of the returned solution to the optimal one.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Approximation algorithms naturally arise in the field of theoretical computer science as a consequence of the widely believed P ≠ NP conjecture.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Under this conjecture, a wide class of optimization problems cannot be solved exactly in polynomial time.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] The field of approximation algorithms, therefore, tries to understand how closely it is possible to approximate optimal solutions to such problems in polynomial time.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] In an overwhelming majority of the cases, the guarantee of such algorithms is a multiplicative one expressed as an approximation ratio or approximation factor i.e., the optimal solution is always guaranteed to be within a (predetermined) multiplicative factor of the returned solution.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] However, there are also many approximation algorithms that provide an additive guarantee on the quality of the returned solution.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] An example of an approximation algorithm with a multiplicative guarantee is the Christofides-Serdyukov algorithm for the Travelling salesman problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] It provides a travelling salesman tour in a metric of length at most 3/2 times that of a shortest such tour.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] A classic example of approximation algorithm providing an additive guarantee is the constructive proof of Vizing’s theorem.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] It shows how to color the edges of an undirected graph with at most $\Delta +1$ colors, where $\Delta$ is the maximum degree of any node.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Since every edge incident on a maximum-degree node must have a different color, the constructive proof of the theorem gives a polynomial-time algorithm that uses at most one additional color than the minimum needed.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] A notable example of an approximation algorithm that provides *both* is the classic approximation algorithm of Lenstra, Shmoys and Tardos for scheduling on unrelated parallel machines.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] The design and analysis of approximation algorithms crucially involves a mathematical proof certifying the quality of the returned solutions in the worst case.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] This distinguishes them from heuristics such as annealing or genetic algorithms, which find reasonably good solutions on some inputs, but provide no clear indication at the outset on when they may succeed or fail.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] There is widespread interest in theoretical computer science to better understand the limits to which we can approximate certain famous optimization problems.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] For example, one of the long-standing open questions in computer science is to determine whether there is an algorithm that outperforms the 2-approximation for the Steiner Forest problem by Agrawal et al.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] The desire to understand hard optimization problems from the perspective of approximability is motivated by the discovery of surprising mathematical connections and broadly applicable techniques to design algorithms for hard optimization problems.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] One well-known example of the former is the Goemans–Williamson algorithm for maximum cut, which solves a graph theoretic problem using a semidefinite program coming from the first level of the sum of squares hierarchy.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] A simple example of an approximation algorithm is one for the minimum vertex cover problem, where the goal is to choose the smallest set of vertices such that every edge in the input graph contains at least one chosen vertex.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] One way to find a vertex cover is to repeat the following process: find an uncovered edge, add both its endpoints to the cover, and remove all edges incident to either vertex from the graph.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] As any vertex cover of the input graph must use a distinct vertex to cover each edge that was considered in the process (since it forms a matching), the vertex cover produced, therefore, is at most twice as large as the optimal one.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] In other words, this is a constant-factor approximation algorithm with an approximation factor of 2.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Under the recent unique games conjecture, this factor is even the best possible one.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Others are impossible to approximate within any constant, or even polynomial, factor unless P = NP, as in the case of the maximum clique problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Therefore, an important benefit of studying approximation algorithms is a fine-grained classification of the difficulty of various NP-hard problems beyond the one afforded by the theory of NP-completeness.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] In other words, although NP-complete problems may be equivalent (under polynomial-time reductions) to each other from the perspective of exact solutions, the corresponding optimization problems behave very differently from the perspective of approximate solutions.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] By now there are several established techniques to design approximation algorithms.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] This involves modeling the considered problem with an appropriate mathematical programming formulation (typically a convex programming) such as Linear programming, Semidefinite programming, etc, to obtain a relaxation of solutions for the problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Then further algorithmic techniques for these formulations are applied.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Embedding the problem in some metric and then solving the problem on the metric.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Random sampling and the use of randomness in general in conjunction with the methods above.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] While approximation algorithms always provide an a priori worst case guarantee (be it additive or multiplicative), in some cases they also provide an a posteriori guarantee that is often much better.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] This is often the case for algorithms that work by solving a convex relaxation of the optimization problem on the given input.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] For example, there is a different approximation algorithm for minimum vertex cover that solves a linear programming relaxation to find a vertex cover that is at most twice the value of the relaxation.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Since the value of the relaxation is never larger than the size of the optimal vertex cover, this yields another 2-approximation algorithm.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] While this is similar to the a priori guarantee of the previous approximation algorithm, the guarantee of the latter can be much better (indeed when the value of the LP relaxation is far from the size of the optimal vertex cover).
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Approximation algorithms as a research area is closely related to and informed by inapproximability theory where the non-existence of efficient algorithms with certain approximation ratios is proved (conditioned on widely believed hypotheses such as the P ≠ NP conjecture) by means of reductions.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] In the case of the metric traveling salesman problem, the best known inapproximability result rules out algorithms with an approximation ratio less than 123/122 ≈ 1.008196 unless P = NP, Karpinski, Lampis, Schmied.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Coupled with the knowledge of the existence of Christofides' 1.5 approximation algorithm, this tells us that the threshold of approximability for metric traveling salesman (if it exists) is somewhere between 123/122 and 1.5.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] While inapproximability results have been proved since the 1970s, such results were obtained by ad hoc means and no systematic understanding was available at the time.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] It is only since the 1990 result of Feige, Goldwasser, Lovász, Safra and Szegedy on the inapproximability of Independent Set and the famous PCP theorem, that modern tools for proving inapproximability results were uncovered.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] The PCP theorem, for example, shows that Johnson's 1974 approximation algorithms for Max SAT, set cover, independent set and coloring all achieve the optimal approximation ratio, assuming P ≠ NP.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Not all approximation algorithms are suitable for direct practical applications.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Implementation and running time issues aside, the guarantees provided by approximation algorithms may themselves not be strong enough to justify their consideration in practice.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Despite their inability to be used "out of the box" in practical applications, the ideas and insights behind the design of such algorithms can often be incorporated in other ways in practical algorithms.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] In this way, the study of even very expensive algorithms is not a completely theoretical pursuit as they can yield valuable insights.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] In other cases, even if the initial results are of purely theoretical interest, over time, with an improved understanding, the algorithms may be refined to become more practical.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] One such example is the initial PTAS for Euclidean TSP by Sanjeev Arora (and independently by Joseph Mitchell) which had a prohibitive running time of $n^{O(1/\epsilon )}$ for a $1+\epsilon$ approximation.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Yet, within a year these ideas were incorporated into a near-linear time $O(n\log n)$ algorithm for any constant $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Given a feasible solution $s\in S(i)$ , with $s\neq s^{*}$ , we would want a guarantee of the quality of the solution, which is a performance to be guaranteed (approximation factor).
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] The approximation can be proven *tight* (*tight approximation*) by demonstrating that there exist instances where the algorithm performs at the approximation limit, indicating the tightness of the bound.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] In this case, it's enough to construct an input instance designed to force the algorithm into a worst-case scenario.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] For some approximation algorithms it is possible to prove certain properties about the approximation of the optimum result.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] The factor *ρ* is called the *relative performance guarantee*.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] where *f*(*y*) is the value/cost of the solution *y* for the instance *x*.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Clearly, the performance guarantee is greater than or equal to 1 and equal to 1 if and only if *y* is an optimal solution.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] If an algorithm *A* guarantees to return solutions with a performance guarantee of at most *r*(*n*), then *A* is said to be an *r*(*n*)-approximation algorithm and has an *approximation ratio* of *r*(*n*).
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Likewise, a problem with an *r*(*n*)-approximation algorithm is said to be r*(*n*)*-*approximable* or have an approximation ratio of *r*(*n*).
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] For minimization problems, the two different guarantees provide the same result and that for maximization problems, a relative performance guarantee of ρ is equivalent to a performance guarantee of $r=\rho ^{-1}$ .
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] In the literature, both definitions are common but it is clear which definition is used since, for maximization problems, as ρ ≤ 1 while r ≥ 1.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] That is to say that $\mathrm {P} _{A}$ is the largest bound on the approximation ratio, *r*, that one sees over all possible instances of the problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] That is to say that it is the same as the *absolute performance ratio*, with a lower bound *n* on the size of problem instances.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] These two types of ratios are used because there exist algorithms where the difference between these two is significant.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] In the literature, an approximation ratio for a maximization (minimization) problem of *c* - ϵ (min: *c* + ϵ) means that the algorithm has an approximation ratio of *c* ∓ ϵ for arbitrary ϵ > 0 but that the ratio has not (or cannot) be shown for ϵ = 0.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] An example of this is the optimal inapproximability — inexistence of approximation — ratio of 7 / 8 + ϵ for satisfiable MAX-3SAT instances due to Johan Håstad.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] As mentioned previously, when *c* = 1, the problem is said to have a polynomial-time approximation scheme.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] An ϵ-term may appear when an approximation algorithm introduces a multiplicative error and a constant error while the minimum optimum of instances of size *n* goes to infinity as *n* does.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] In this case, the approximation ratio is *c* ∓ *k* / OPT = *c* ∓ o(1) for some constants *c* and *k*.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] Given arbitrary ϵ > 0, one can choose a large enough *N* such that the term *k* / OPT < ϵ for every *n ≥ N*.
[src:christofides-tsp/approximation-algorithm] For every fixed ϵ, instances of size *n < N* can be solved by brute force, thereby showing an approximation ratio — existence of approximation algorithms with a guarantee — of *c* ∓ ϵ for every ϵ > 0.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] The **Christofides algorithm** or **Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm** is an algorithm for finding approximate solutions to the travelling salesman problem, on instances where the distances form a metric space (they are symmetric and obey the triangle inequality).
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] It is an approximation algorithm that guarantees that its solutions will be within a factor of 3/2 of the optimal solution length, and is named after Nicos Christofides and Anatoliy Serdyukov (Russian: Анатолий Иванович Сердюков).
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Christofides published the algorithm in 1976; Serdyukov discovered it independently in 1976 but published it in 1978.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Let *G* = (*V*,*w*) be an instance of the travelling salesman problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] That is, G is a complete graph on the set V of vertices, and the function w assigns a nonnegative real weight to every edge of G.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] According to the triangle inequality, for every three vertices u, v, and x, it should be the case that *w*(*uv*) + *w*(*vx*) ≥ *w*(*ux*).
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Then the algorithm can be described in pseudocode as follows.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Let O be the set of vertices with odd degree in T.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] By the handshaking lemma, O has an even number of vertices.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Find a minimum-weight perfect matching M in the subgraph induced in G by O.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Combine the edges of M and T to form a connected multigraph H in which each vertex has even degree.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Make the circuit found in previous step into a Hamiltonian circuit by skipping repeated vertices (*shortcutting*).
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Steps 5 and 6 do not necessarily yield only a single result; as such, the heuristic can give several different paths.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] The worst-case complexity of the algorithm is dominated by the perfect matching step, which has $O(n^{3})$ complexity.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Serdyukov's paper claimed $O(n^{3}\log n)$ complexity, because the author was only aware of a less efficient perfect matching algorithm.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] The cost of the solution produced by the algorithm is within 3/2 of the optimum.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] To prove this, let C be the optimal traveling salesman tour.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Removing an edge from C produces a spanning tree, which must have weight at least that of the minimum spanning tree, implying that *w*(*T*) ≤ *w*(*C*) - lower bound to the cost of the optimal solution.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] The algorithm addresses the problem that T is not a tour by identifying all the odd degree vertices in T; since the sum of degrees in any graph is even (by the handshaking lemma), there is an even number of such vertices.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] The algorithm finds a minimum-weight perfect matching M among the odd-degree ones.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Next, number the vertices of O in cyclic order around C, and partition C into two sets of paths: the ones in which the first path vertex in cyclic order has an odd number and the ones in which the first path vertex has an even number.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Each set of paths corresponds to a perfect matching of O that matches the two endpoints of each path, and the weight of this matching is at most equal to the weight of the paths.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] In fact, each path endpoint will be connected to another endpoint, which also has an odd number of visits due to the nature of the tour.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Since these two sets of paths partition the edges of C, one of the two sets has at most half of the weight of C, and thanks to the triangle inequality its corresponding matching has weight that is also at most half the weight of C.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] The minimum-weight perfect matching can have no larger weight, so *w*(*M*) ≤ *w*(*C*)/2.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Adding the weights of T and M gives the weight of the Euler tour, at most 3*w*(*C*)/2.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Thanks to the triangle inequality, even though the Euler tour might revisit vertices, shortcutting does not increase the weight, so the weight of the output is also at most 3*w*(*C*)/2.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] There exist inputs to the travelling salesman problem that cause the Christofides algorithm to find a solution whose approximation ratio is arbitrarily close to 3/2.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] One such class of inputs are formed by a path of n vertices, with the path edges having weight 1, together with a set of edges connecting vertices two steps apart in the path with weight 1 + *ε* for a number *ε* chosen close to zero but positive.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] All remaining edges of the complete graph have distances given by the shortest paths in this subgraph.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Then the minimum spanning tree will be given by the path, of length *n* − 1, and the only two odd vertices will be the path endpoints, whose perfect matching consists of a single edge with weight approximately *n*/2.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] The union of the tree and the matching is a cycle, with no possible shortcuts, and with weight approximately 3*n*/2.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] However, the optimal solution uses the edges of weight 1 + *ε* together with two weight-1 edges incident to the endpoints of the path, and has total weight (1 + *ε*)(*n* − 2) + 2, close to n for small values of *ε*.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Hence we obtain an approximation ratio of 3/2.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] This algorithm is no longer the best polynomial time approximation algorithm for the TSP on general metric spaces.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Karlin, Klein, and Gharan introduced a randomized approximation algorithm with approximation ratio 1.5 − 10−36.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] It follows similar principles to Christofides' algorithm, but uses a randomly chosen tree from a carefully chosen random distribution in place of the minimum spanning tree.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] The paper received a best paper award at the 2021 Symposium on Theory of Computing.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] For each constant c this time bound is in polynomial time, so this is called a polynomial-time approximation scheme (PTAS).
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Mitchell were awarded the Gödel Prize in 2010 for their simultaneous discovery of a PTAS for the Euclidean TSP.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] Methods based on the Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm can also be used to approximate the stacker crane problem, a generalization of the TSP in which the input consists of ordered pairs of points from a metric space that must be traversed consecutively and in order.
[src:christofides-tsp/christofides-algorithm] For this problem, it achieves an approximation ratio of 9/5.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] A **minimum spanning tree** (**MST**) or **minimum weight spanning tree** is a subset of the edges of a connected, edge-weighted undirected graph that connects all the vertices together, without any cycles and with the minimum possible total edge weight.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] That is, it is a spanning tree whose sum of edge weights is as small as possible.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] More generally, any edge-weighted undirected graph (not necessarily connected) has a **minimum spanning forest**, which is a union of the minimum spanning trees for its connected components.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] There are many use cases for minimum spanning trees.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] One example is a telecommunications company trying to lay cable in a new neighborhood.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] If it is constrained to bury the cable only along certain paths (e.g. roads), then there would be a graph containing the points (e.g. houses) connected by those paths.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Some of the paths might be more expensive, because they are longer, or require the cable to be buried deeper; these paths would be represented by edges with larger weights.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Currency is an acceptable unit for edge weight – there is no requirement for edge lengths to obey normal rules of geometry such as the triangle inequality.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] A *spanning tree* for that graph would be a subset of those paths that has no cycles but still connects every house; there might be several spanning trees possible.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] A *minimum spanning tree* would be one with the lowest total cost, representing the least expensive path for laying the cable.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] If there are n vertices in the graph, then each spanning tree has *n* − 1 edges.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] There may be several minimum spanning trees of the same weight; in particular, if all the edge weights of a given graph are the same, then every spanning tree of that graph is minimum.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Since A and B differ despite containing the same nodes, there is at least one edge that belongs to one but not the other.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Among such edges, let *e*1 be the one with least weight; this choice is unique because the edge weights are all distinct.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Without loss of generality, assume *e*1 is in A.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] As B is an MST, {*e*1} ∪ *B* must contain a cycle C with *e*1.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] As a tree, A contains no cycles, therefore C must have an edge *e*2 that is not in A.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Since *e*1 was chosen as the unique lowest-weight edge among those belonging to exactly one of A and B, the weight of *e*2 must be greater than the weight of *e*1.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] As *e*1 and *e*2 are part of the cycle C, replacing *e*2 with *e*1 in B therefore yields a spanning tree with a smaller weight.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] This contradicts the assumption that B is an MST.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] More generally, if the edge weights are not all distinct then only the (multi-)set of weights in minimum spanning trees is certain to be unique; it is the same for all minimum spanning trees.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] If the weights are *positive*, then a minimum spanning tree is, in fact, a minimum-cost subgraph connecting all vertices, since if a subgraph contains a cycle, removing any edge along that cycle will decrease its cost and preserve connectivity.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Proof: Assume the contrary, i.e. that e belongs to an MST *T*1.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Then deleting e will break *T*1 into two subtrees with the two ends of e in different subtrees.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The remainder of C reconnects the subtrees, hence there is an edge f of C with ends in different subtrees, i.e., it reconnects the subtrees into a tree *T*2 with weight less than that of *T*1, because the weight of f is less than the weight of e.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Proof: Assume that there is an MST T that does not contain e.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Adding e to T will produce a cycle, that crosses the cut once at e and crosses back at another edge e'.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Deleting e' we get a spanning tree *T*∖{*e'*} ∪ {*e*} of strictly smaller weight than T.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] This contradicts the assumption that T was a MST.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] By a similar argument, if more than one edge is of minimum weight across a cut, then each such edge is contained in some minimum spanning tree.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Proof: if e was not included in the MST, removing any of the (larger cost) edges in the cycle formed after adding e to the MST, would yield a spanning tree of smaller weight.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] If T is a tree of MST edges, then we can *contract* T into a single vertex while maintaining the invariant that the MST of the contracted graph plus T gives the MST for the graph before contraction.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] In all of the algorithms below, m is the number of edges in the graph and n is the number of vertices.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The first algorithm for finding a minimum spanning tree was developed by Czech scientist Otakar Borůvka in 1926 (see Borůvka's algorithm).
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Its purpose was an efficient electrical coverage of Moravia.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The algorithm proceeds in a sequence of stages.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] In each stage, called *Boruvka step*, it identifies a forest F consisting of the minimum-weight edge incident to each vertex in the graph G, then forms the graph *G*1 = *G* \ *F* as the input to the next step.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Here *G* \ *F* denotes the graph derived from G by contracting edges in F (by the Cut property, these edges belong to the MST).
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Since the number of vertices is reduced by at least half in each step, Boruvka's algorithm takes *O*(*m* log *n*) time.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] A second algorithm is Prim's algorithm, which was invented by Vojtěch Jarník in 1930 and rediscovered by Prim in 1957 and Dijkstra in 1959.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Basically, it grows the MST (T) one edge at a time.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Initially, T contains an arbitrary vertex.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] In each step, T is augmented with a least-weight edge (*x*,*y*) such that x is in T and y is not yet in T.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] By the Cut property, all edges added to T are in the MST.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Its run-time is either *O*(*m* log *n*) or *O*(*m* + *n* log *n*), depending on the data-structures used.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] A third algorithm commonly in use is Kruskal's algorithm, which also takes *O*(*m* log *n*) time.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] A fourth algorithm, not as commonly used, is the reverse-delete algorithm, which is the reverse of Kruskal's algorithm.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Its runtime is O(*m* log *n* (log log *n*)3).
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] All four of these are greedy algorithms.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Since they run in polynomial time, the problem of finding such trees is in **FP**, and related decision problems such as determining whether a particular edge is in the MST or determining if the minimum total weight exceeds a certain value are in **P**.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Several researchers have tried to find more computationally-efficient algorithms.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] In a comparison model, in which the only allowed operations on edge weights are pairwise comparisons, Karger, Klein & Tarjan (1995) found a linear time randomized algorithm based on a combination of Borůvka's algorithm and the reverse-delete algorithm.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The fastest non-randomized comparison-based algorithm with known complexity, by Bernard Chazelle, is based on the soft heap, an approximate priority queue.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Its running time is *O*(*m* α(*m*,*n*)), where α is the classical functional inverse of the Ackermann function.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The function α grows extremely slowly, so that for all practical purposes it may be considered a constant no greater than 4; thus Chazelle's algorithm takes very close to linear time.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] *m*/*n* ≥ log log log *n*), then a deterministic algorithm by Fredman and Tarjan finds the MST in time O(*m*).
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The algorithm executes a number of phases.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Each phase executes Prim's algorithm many times, each for a limited number of steps.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The run-time of each phase is O(*m* + *n*).
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] If the number of vertices before a phase is n', the number of vertices remaining after a phase is at most ${\tfrac {n'}{2^{m/n'}}}$ .
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Hence, at most log**n* phases are needed, which gives a linear run-time for dense graphs.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] There are other algorithms that work in linear time on dense graphs.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] If the edge weights are integers represented in binary, then deterministic algorithms are known that solve the problem in *O*(*m* + *n*) integer operations.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Whether the problem can be solved *deterministically* for a *general graph* in *linear time* by a comparison-based algorithm remains an open question.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Deterministic algorithms are known that solve the problem for planar graphs in linear time.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] By the Euler characteristic of planar graphs, *m* ≤ 3*n* - 6 ∈ *O*(*n*), so this is in time *O*(*n*).
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Given graph G where the nodes and edges are fixed but the weights are unknown, it is possible to construct a binary decision tree (DT) for calculating the MST for any permutation of weights.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Each internal node of the DT contains a comparison between two edges, e.g.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] "Is the weight of the edge between x and y larger than the weight of the edge between w and z?".
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The two children of the node correspond to the two possible answers "yes" or "no".
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] In each leaf of the DT, there is a list of edges from G that correspond to an MST.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The runtime complexity of a DT is the largest number of queries required to find the MST, which is just the depth of the DT.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] A DT for a graph G is called *optimal* if it has the smallest depth of all correct DTs for G.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] For every integer r, it is possible to find optimal decision trees for all graphs on r vertices by brute-force search.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Seth Pettie and Vijaya Ramachandran have found a provably optimal deterministic comparison-based minimum spanning tree algorithm.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The following is a simplified description of the algorithm.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Partition the graph to components with at most r vertices in each component.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] This partition uses a soft heap, which "corrupts" a small number of the edges of the graph.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Use the optimal decision trees to find an MST for the uncorrupted subgraph within each component.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Add back the corrupted edges to the resulting forest to form a subgraph guaranteed to contain the minimum spanning tree, and smaller by a constant factor than the starting graph.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Apply the optimal algorithm recursively to this graph.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The runtime of all steps in the algorithm is *O*(*m*), *except for the step of using the decision trees*.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The runtime of this step is unknown, but it has been proved that it is optimal - no algorithm can do better than the optimal decision tree.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Thus, this algorithm has the peculiar property that it is *provably optimal* although its runtime complexity is *unknown*.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Research has also considered parallel algorithms for the minimum spanning tree problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] With a linear number of processors it is possible to solve the problem in *O*(log *n*) time.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The problem can also be approached in a distributed manner.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] If each node is considered a computer and no node knows anything except its own connected links, one can still calculate the distributed minimum spanning tree.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Frieze and Steele also proved convergence in probability.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Svante Janson proved a central limit theorem for weight of the MST.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] For uniform random weights in $[0,1]$ , the exact expected size of the minimum spanning tree has been computed for small complete graphs.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] There is a fractional variant of the MST, in which each edge is allowed to appear "fractionally".
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Formally, a **fractional spanning set** of a graph (V,E) is a nonnegative function *f* on *E* such that, for every non-trivial subset *W* of *V* (i.e., *W* is neither empty nor equal to *V*), the sum of *f*(*e*) over all edges connecting a node of *W* with a node of *V*\*W* is at least 1.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Intuitively, *f*(*e*) represents the fraction of e that is contained in the spanning set.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] A **minimum fractional spanning set** is a fractional spanning set for which the sum $\sum _{e\in E}f(e)\cdot w(e)$ is as small as possible.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] If the fractions *f*(*e*) are forced to be in {0,1}, then the set *T* of edges with f(e)=1 are a spanning set, as every node or subset of nodes is connected to the rest of the graph by at least one edge of *T*.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Moreover, if *f* minimizes $\sum _{e\in E}f(e)\cdot w(e)$ , then the resulting spanning set is necessarily a tree, since if it contained a cycle, then an edge could be removed without affecting the spanning condition.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] The fractional MST problem can be solved in polynomial time using the ellipsoid method.
[src:christofides-tsp/minimum-spanning-tree] Minimum spanning trees have direct applications in the design of networks, including computer networks, telecommunications networks, transportation networks, water supply networks, and electrical grids (which they were first invented for, as mentioned above).
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] In graph theory and combinatorial optimization, **Guan's route problem**, the **Chinese postman problem**, **postman tour** or **route inspection problem** is to find a shortest closed path or circuit that visits every edge of an (connected) undirected graph at least once.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] When the graph has an Eulerian circuit (a closed walk that covers every edge once), that circuit is an optimal solution.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] Otherwise, the optimization problem is to find the smallest number of graph edges to duplicate (or the subset of edges with the minimum possible total weight) so that the resulting multigraph does have an Eulerian circuit.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] It can be solved in polynomial time, unlike the Travelling Salesman Problem which is NP-hard.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] It is different from the Travelling Salesman Problem in that the travelling salesman cannot repeat visited nodes and does not have to visit every edge.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] The problem was originally studied by the Chinese mathematician Meigu Guan in 1960, whose Chinese paper was translated into English in 1962.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] The original name "Chinese postman problem" was coined in his honor; different sources credit the coinage either to Alan J.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] Goldman or Jack Edmonds, both of whom were at the U.S.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] National Bureau of Standards at the time.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] A generalization takes as input any set *T* of evenly many vertices, and must produce as output a minimum-weight edge set in the graph whose odd-degree vertices are precisely those of *T*.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] This problem, the ***T*-join problem**, is also solvable in polynomial time by the same approach that solves the postman problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] The undirected route inspection problem can be solved in polynomial time by an algorithm based on the concept of a *T*-join.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] Let *T* be a set of vertices in a graph.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] An edge set *J* is called a *T***-join** if the collection of vertices that have an odd number of incident edges in *J* is exactly the set *T*.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] A *T*-join exists whenever every connected component of the graph contains an even number of vertices in *T*.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] The *T***-join problem** is to find a *T*-join with the minimum possible number of edges or the minimum possible total weight.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] For any *T*, a smallest *T*-join (when it exists) necessarily consists of ${\tfrac {1}{2}}|T|$ paths that join the vertices of *T* in pairs.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] The paths will be such that the total length or total weight of all of them is as small as possible.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] In an optimal solution, no two of these paths will share any edge, but they may have shared vertices.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] A minimum *T*-join can be obtained by constructing a complete graph on the vertices of *T*, with edges that represent shortest paths in the given input graph, and then finding a minimum weight perfect matching in this complete graph.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] The edges of this matching represent paths in the original graph, whose union forms the desired *T*-join.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] Both constructing the complete graph, and then finding a matching in it, can be done in O(*n*3) computational steps.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] For the route inspection problem, *T* should be chosen as the set of all odd-degree vertices.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] By the assumptions of the problem, the whole graph is connected (otherwise no tour exists), and by the handshaking lemma it has an even number of odd vertices, so a *T*-join always exists.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] Doubling the edges of a *T*-join causes the given graph to become an Eulerian multigraph (a connected graph in which every vertex has even degree), from which it follows that it has an Euler tour, a tour that visits each edge of the multigraph exactly once.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] This tour will be an optimal solution to the route inspection problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] On a directed graph, the same general ideas apply, but different techniques must be used.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] If the directed graph is Eulerian, one need only find an Euler cycle.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] If it is not, one must find *T*-joins, which in this case entails finding paths from vertices with an in-degree greater than their out-degree to those with an out-degree greater than their in-degree such that they would make in-degree of every vertex equal to its out-degree.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] This can be solved as an instance of the minimum-cost flow problem in which there is one unit of supply for every unit of excess in-degree, and one unit of demand for every unit of excess out-degree.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] As such it is solvable in O(|*V*|2|*E*|) time.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] A solution exists if and only if the given graph is strongly connected.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] Various combinatorial problems have been reduced to the Chinese Postman Problem, including finding a maximum cut in a planar graph and a minimum-mean length circuit in an undirected graph.
[src:christofides-tsp/route-inspection-problem] A few variants of the Chinese Postman Problem have been studied and shown to be NP-complete.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The travelling purchaser problem, the vehicle routing problem and the ring star problem are three generalizations of TSP.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The decision version of the TSP (where given a length *L*, the task is to decide whether the graph has a tour whose length is at most *L*) belongs to the class of NP-complete problems.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Thus, it is possible that the worst-case running time for any algorithm for the TSP increases superpolynomially (but no more than exponentially) with the number of cities.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The problem was first formulated in 1930 and is one of the most intensively studied problems in optimization.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] It is used as a benchmark for many optimization methods.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Even though the problem is computationally difficult, many heuristics and exact algorithms are known, so that some instances with tens of thousands of cities can be solved completely, and even problems with millions of cities can be approximated within a small fraction of 1%.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP has several applications even in its purest formulation, such as planning, logistics, and the manufacture of microchips.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In warehouse operations, order picking routes are often modelled as variants of the travelling salesman problem, where a picker must visit multiple storage locations and return to a start or drop-off point while minimizing travel distance or time.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Slightly modified, it appears as a sub-problem in many areas, such as DNA sequencing.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In these applications, the concept *city* represents, for example, customers, soldering points, or DNA fragments, and the concept *distance* represents travelling times or cost, or a similarity measure between DNA fragments.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP also appears in astronomy, as astronomers observing many sources want to minimize the time spent moving the telescope between the sources; in such problems, the TSP can be embedded inside an optimal control problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In many applications, additional constraints such as limited resources or time windows may be imposed.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The origins of the travelling salesman problem are unclear.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] A handbook for travelling salesmen from 1832 mentions the problem and includes example tours through Germany and Switzerland, but contains no mathematical treatment.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP was mathematically formulated in the 19th century by the Irish mathematician William Rowan Hamilton and by the British mathematician Thomas Kirkman.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Hamilton's icosian game was a recreational puzzle based on finding a Hamiltonian cycle.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] It was first considered mathematically in the 1930s by Merrill M.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Flood, who was looking to solve a school bus routing problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Hassler Whitney at Princeton University generated interest in the problem, which he called the "48 states problem".
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In the 1950s and 1960s, the problem became increasingly popular in scientific circles in Europe and the United States after the RAND Corporation in Santa Monica offered prizes for steps in solving the problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Notable contributions were made by George Dantzig, Delbert Ray Fulkerson, and Selmer M.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Johnson from the RAND Corporation, who expressed the problem as an integer linear program and developed the cutting plane method for its solution.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] They wrote what is considered the seminal paper on the subject in which, with these new methods, they solved an instance with 49 cities to optimality by constructing a tour and proving that no other tour could be shorter.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Dantzig, Fulkerson, and Johnson, however, speculated that, given a near-optimal solution, one may be able to find optimality or prove optimality by adding a small number of extra inequalities (cuts).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] They used this idea to solve their initial 49-city problem using a string model.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] They found they only needed 26 cuts to come to a solution for their 49 city problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] While this paper did not give an algorithmic approach to TSP problems, the ideas that lay within it were indispensable to later creating exact solution methods for the TSP, though it would take 15 years to find an algorithmic approach in creating these cuts.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] As well as cutting plane methods, Dantzig, Fulkerson, and Johnson used branch-and-bound algorithms perhaps for the first time.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Halton, and John Hammersley published an article entitled "The Shortest Path Through Many Points" in the journal of the Cambridge Philosophical Society.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The Beardwood–Halton–Hammersley theorem provides a practical solution to the travelling salesman problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The authors derived an asymptotic formula to determine the length of the shortest route for a salesman who starts at a home or office and visits a fixed number of locations before returning to the start.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In the following decades, the problem was studied by many researchers from mathematics, computer science, chemistry, physics, and other sciences.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] One method of doing this was to create a minimum spanning tree of the graph and then double all its edges, which produces the bound that the length of an optimal tour is at most twice the weight of a minimum spanning tree.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In 1976, Christofides and Serdyukov (independently of each other) made a big advance in this direction: the Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm yields a solution that, in the worst case, is at most 1.5 times longer than the optimal solution.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] As the algorithm was simple and quick, many hoped it would give way to a near-optimal solution method.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] However, this hope for improvement did not immediately materialize, and the Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm remained the method with the best worst-case scenario until 2011, when a (very) slightly improved approximation algorithm was developed for the subset of "graphical" TSPs.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In 2020, this tiny improvement was extended to the full (metric) TSP.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Karp showed in 1972 that the Hamiltonian cycle problem was NP-complete, which implies the NP-hardness of TSP.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This supplied a mathematical explanation for the apparent computational difficulty of finding optimal tours.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Great progress was made in the late 1970s and 1980, when Grötschel, Padberg, Rinaldi and others managed to exactly solve instances with up to 2,392 cities, using cutting planes and branch-and-bound.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In the 1990s, Applegate, Bixby, Chvátal, and Cook developed the program *Concorde* that has been used in many recent record solutions.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Gerhard Reinelt published the TSPLIB in 1991, a collection of benchmark instances of varying difficulty, which has been used by many research groups for comparing results.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In 2006, Cook and others computed an optimal tour through an 85,900-city instance given by a microchip layout problem, currently the largest solved TSPLIB instance.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] For many other instances with millions of cities, solutions can be found that are guaranteed to be within 2–3% of an optimal tour.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] TSP can be modeled as an undirected weighted graph, such that cities are the graph's vertices, paths are the graph's edges, and a path's distance is the edge's weight.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] It is a minimization problem starting and finishing at a specified vertex after having visited each other vertex exactly once.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Often, the model is a complete graph (i.e., each pair of vertices is connected by an edge).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] If no path exists between two cities, then adding a sufficiently long edge will complete the graph without affecting the optimal tour.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In the *symmetric TSP*, the distance between two cities is the same in each opposite direction, forming an undirected graph.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This symmetry halves the number of possible solutions.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In the *asymmetric TSP*, paths may not exist in both directions or the distances might be different, forming a directed graph.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Traffic congestion, one-way streets, and airfares for cities with different departure and arrival fees are real-world considerations that could yield a TSP problem in asymmetric form.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP can be formulated as an integer linear program.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Two notable formulations are the Miller–Tucker–Zemlin (MTZ) formulation and the Dantzig–Fulkerson–Johnson (DFJ) formulation.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The DFJ formulation is stronger, though the MTZ formulation is still useful in certain settings.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Common to both these formulations is that one labels the cities with the numbers $1,\ldots ,n$ and takes $c_{ij}>0$ to be the cost (distance) from city i to city j .
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] It is because these are 0/1 variables that the formulations become integer programs; all other constraints are purely linear.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Without further constraints, the $\{x_{ij}\}_{i,j}$ will effectively range over all subsets of the set of edges, which is very far from the sets of edges in a tour, and allows for a trivial minimum where all $x_{ij}=0$ .
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The MTZ and DFJ formulations differ in how they express this final requirement as linear constraints.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Merely requiring $u_{j}\geq u_{i}+x_{ij}$ would *not* achieve that, because this also requires $u_{j}\geq u_{i}$ when $x_{ij}=0,$ which is not correct.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The first set of equalities requires that each city is arrived at from exactly one other city, and the second set of equalities requires that from each city there is a departure to exactly one other city.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The last constraint enforces that there is only a single tour covering all cities, and not two or more disjointed tours that only collectively cover all cities.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Take $c_{ij}>0$ to be the distance from city *i* to city *j*.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The last constraint of the DFJ formulation—called a *subtour elimination* constraint—ensures that no proper subset Q can form a sub-tour, so the solution returned is a single tour and not the union of smaller tours.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Intuitively, for each proper subset Q of the cities, the constraint requires that there be fewer edges than cities in Q: if there were to be as many edges in Q as cities in Q, that would represent a subtour of the cities of Q.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Because this leads to an exponential number of possible constraints, in practice it is solved with row generation.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The most direct solution would be to try all permutations (ordered combinations) and see which one is cheapest (using brute-force search).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The running time for this approach lies within a polynomial factor of $O(n!)$ , the factorial of the number of cities, so this solution becomes impractical even for only 20 cities.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] One of the earliest applications of dynamic programming is the Held–Karp algorithm, which solves the problem in time $O(n^{2}2^{n})$ .
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Improving these time bounds seems to be difficult.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, it has not been determined whether a classical exact algorithm for TSP that runs in time $O(1.9999^{n})$ exists.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The currently best quantum exact algorithm for TSP due to Ambainis et al. runs in time $O(1.728^{n})$ .
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] An exact solution for 15,112 German towns from TSPLIB was found in 2001 using the cutting-plane method proposed by George Dantzig, Ray Fulkerson, and Selmer M.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Johnson in 1954, based on linear programming.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The computations were performed on a network of 110 processors located at Rice University and Princeton University.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The total computation time was equivalent to 22.6 years on a single 500 MHz Alpha processor.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In May 2004, the travelling salesman problem of visiting all 24,978 towns in Sweden was solved: a tour of length approximately 72,500 kilometres was found, and it was proven that no shorter tour exists.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In March 2005, the travelling salesman problem of visiting all 33,810 points in a circuit board was solved using *Concorde TSP Solver*: a tour of length 66,048,945 units was found, and it was proven that no shorter tour exists.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The computation took approximately 15.7 CPU-years (Cook et al.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In April 2006 an instance with 85,900 points was solved using *Concorde TSP Solver*, taking over 136 CPU-years; see Applegate et al.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Various heuristics and approximation algorithms, which quickly yield good solutions, have been devised.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] These include the multi-fragment algorithm.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Modern methods can find solutions for extremely large problems (millions of cities) within a reasonable time which are, with a high probability, just 2–3% away from the optimal solution.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Several categories of heuristics are recognized.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The nearest neighbour (NN) algorithm (a greedy algorithm) lets the salesman choose the nearest unvisited city as his next move.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This algorithm quickly yields an effectively short route.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] For *N* cities randomly distributed on a plane, the algorithm on average yields a path 25% longer than the shortest possible path; however, there exist many specially-arranged city distributions which make the NN algorithm give the worst route.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This is true for both asymmetric and symmetric TSPs.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Rosenkrantz et al. showed that the NN algorithm has the approximation factor $\Theta (\log |V|)$ for instances satisfying the triangle inequality.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] A variation of the NN algorithm, called nearest fragment (NF) operator, which connects a group (fragment) of nearest unvisited cities, can find shorter routes with successive iterations.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The NF operator can also be applied on an initial solution obtained by the NN algorithm for further improvement in an elitist model, where only better solutions are accepted.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The bitonic tour of a set of points is the minimum-perimeter monotone polygon that has the points as its vertices; it can be computed efficiently with dynamic programming.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Another constructive heuristic, Match Twice and Stitch (MTS), performs two sequential matchings, where the second matching is executed after deleting all the edges of the first matching, to yield a set of cycles.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The cycles are then stitched to produce the final tour.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The algorithm of Christofides and Serdyukov follows a similar outline but combines the minimum spanning tree with a solution of another problem, minimum-weight perfect matching.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This gives a TSP tour which is at most 1.5 times the optimal.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] It was one of the first approximation algorithms, and was in part responsible for drawing attention to approximation algorithms as a practical approach to intractable problems.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] As a matter of fact, the term "algorithm" was not commonly extended to approximation algorithms until later; the Christofides algorithm was initially referred to as the Christofides heuristic.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This algorithm looks at things differently by using a result from graph theory which helps improve on the lower bound of the TSP which originated from doubling the cost of the minimum spanning tree.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Given an Eulerian graph, we can find an Eulerian tour in ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time, so if we had an Eulerian graph with cities from a TSP as vertices, then we can easily see that we could use such a method for finding an Eulerian tour to find a TSP solution.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] By the triangle inequality, we know that the TSP tour can be no longer than the Eulerian tour, and we therefore have a lower bound for the TSP.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Create duplicates for every edge to create an Eulerian graph.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Convert to TSP: if a city is visited twice, then create a shortcut from the city before this in the tour to the one after this.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] To improve the lower bound, a better way of creating an Eulerian graph is needed.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] By the triangle inequality, the best Eulerian graph must have the same cost as the best travelling salesman tour; hence, finding optimal Eulerian graphs is at least as hard as TSP.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] One way of doing this is by minimum weight matching using algorithms with a complexity of $O(n^{3})$ .
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Making a graph into an Eulerian graph starts with the minimum spanning tree; all the vertices of odd order must then be made even, so a matching for the odd-degree vertices must be added, which increases the order of every odd-degree vertex by 1.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This leaves us with a graph where every vertex is of even order, which is thus Eulerian.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Create a matching for the problem with the set of cities of odd order.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The pairwise exchange or 2-opt technique involves iteratively removing two edges and replacing them with two different edges that reconnect the fragments created by edge removal into a new and shorter tour.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Similarly, the 3-opt technique removes 3 edges and reconnects them to form a shorter tour.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] These are special cases of the *k*-opt method.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The label *Lin–Kernighan* is an often heard misnomer for 2-opt; Lin–Kernighan is actually the more general *k*-opt method.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] For Euclidean instances, 2-opt heuristics give on average solutions that are about 5% better than those yielded by Christofides' algorithm.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] If we start with an initial solution made with a greedy algorithm, then the average number of moves greatly decreases again and is ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠; however, for random starts, the average number of moves is ⁠ $O(n\log(n))$ ⁠.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] While this is a small increase in size, the initial number of moves for small problems is 10 times as big for a random start compared to one made from a greedy heuristic.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This is because such 2-opt heuristics exploit 'bad' parts of a solution such as crossings.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] These types of heuristics are often used within vehicle routing problem heuristics to re-optimize route solutions.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The Lin–Kernighan heuristic is a special case of the *V*-opt or variable-opt technique.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Reassemble the remaining fragments into a tour, leaving no disjoint subtours (that is, do not connect a fragment's endpoints together).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This in effect simplifies the TSP under consideration into a much simpler problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Each fragment endpoint can be connected to 2*k* − 2 other possibilities: of 2*k* total fragment endpoints available, the two endpoints of the fragment under consideration are disallowed.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Such a constrained 2*k*-city TSP can then be solved with brute-force methods to find the least-cost recombination of the original fragments.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The most popular of the *k*-opt methods are 3-opt, as introduced by Shen Lin of Bell Labs in 1965.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] A special case of 3-opt is where the edges are not disjoint (two of the edges are adjacent to one another).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In practice, it is often possible to achieve substantial improvement over 2-opt without the combinatorial cost of the general 3-opt by restricting the 3-changes to this special subset where two of the removed edges are adjacent.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This so-called two-and-a-half-opt typically falls roughly midway between 2-opt and 3-opt, both in terms of the quality of tours achieved and the time required to achieve those tours.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The variable-opt method is related to, and a generalization of, the *k*-opt method.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Whereas the *k*-opt methods remove a fixed number (*k*) of edges from the original tour, the variable-opt methods do not fix the size of the edge set to remove.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Instead, they grow the set as the search process continues.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The best-known method in this family is the Lin–Kernighan method (mentioned above as a misnomer for 2-opt).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Shen Lin and Brian Kernighan first published their method in 1972, and it was the most reliable heuristic for solving travelling salesman problems for nearly two decades.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] More advanced variable-opt methods were developed at Bell Labs in the late 1980s by David Johnson and his research team.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] These methods (sometimes called Lin–Kernighan–Johnson) build on the Lin–Kernighan method, adding ideas from tabu search and evolutionary computing.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The basic Lin–Kernighan technique gives results that are guaranteed to be at least 3-opt.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The Lin–Kernighan–Johnson methods compute a Lin–Kernighan tour, and then perturb the tour by what has been described as a mutation that removes at least four edges and reconnects the tour in a different way, then *V*-opting the new tour.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The mutation is often enough to move the tour from the local minimum identified by Lin–Kernighan.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] *V*-opt methods are widely considered the most powerful heuristics for the problem, and are able to address special cases, such as the Hamilton Cycle Problem and other non-metric TSPs that other heuristics fail on.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] For many years, Lin–Kernighan–Johnson had identified optimal solutions for all TSPs where an optimal solution was known and had identified the best-known solutions for all other TSPs on which the method had been tried.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Optimized Markov chain algorithms which use local searching heuristic sub-algorithms can find a route extremely close to the optimal route for 700 to 800 cities.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] TSP is a touchstone for many general heuristics devised for combinatorial optimization such as genetic algorithms, simulated annealing, tabu search, ant colony optimization, river formation dynamics (see swarm intelligence), and the cross entropy method.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This starts with a sub-tour such as the convex hull and then inserts other vertices.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Artificial intelligence researcher Marco Dorigo described in 1993 a method of heuristically generating "good solutions" to the TSP using a simulation of an ant colony called *ACS* (*ant colony system*).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] It models behavior observed in real ants to find short paths between food sources and their nest, an emergent behavior resulting from each ant's preference to follow trail pheromones deposited by other ants.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] ACS sends out a large number of virtual ant agents to explore many possible routes on the map.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Each ant probabilistically chooses the next city to visit based on a heuristic combining the distance to the city and the amount of virtual pheromone deposited on the edge to the city.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The ants explore, depositing pheromone on each edge that they cross, until they have all completed a tour.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] At this point the ant which completed the shortest tour deposits virtual pheromone along its complete tour route (*global trail updating*).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The amount of pheromone deposited is inversely proportional to the tour length: the shorter the tour, the more it deposits.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In the *metric TSP*, also known as *delta-TSP* or Δ-TSP, the intercity distances satisfy the triangle inequality.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The edges then build a metric on the set of vertices.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] When the cities are viewed as points in the plane, many natural distance functions are metrics, and so many natural instances of TSP satisfy this constraint.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The following are some examples of metric TSPs for various metrics.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The last two metrics appear, for example, in routing a machine that drills a given set of holes in a printed circuit board.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The Manhattan metric corresponds to a machine that adjusts first one coordinate, and then the other, so the time to move to a new point is the sum of both movements.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The maximum metric corresponds to a machine that adjusts both coordinates simultaneously, so the time to move to a new point is the slower of the two movements.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In its definition, the TSP does not allow cities to be visited twice, but many applications do not need this constraint.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In such cases, a symmetric, non-metric instance can be reduced to a metric one.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This replaces the original graph with a complete graph in which the inter-city distance $d_{AB}$ is replaced by the shortest path length between *A* and *B* in the original graph.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] For points in the Euclidean plane, the optimal solution to the travelling salesman problem forms a simple polygon through all of the points, a polygonalization of the points.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Any non-optimal solution with crossings can be made into a shorter solution without crossings by local optimizations.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The Euclidean distance obeys the triangle inequality, so the Euclidean TSP forms a special case of metric TSP.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] However, even when the input points have integer coordinates, their distances generally take the form of square roots, and the length of a tour is a sum of radicals, making it difficult to perform the symbolic computation needed to perform exact comparisons of the lengths of different tours.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Like the general TSP, the exact Euclidean TSP is NP-hard, but the issue with sums of radicals is an obstacle to proving that its decision version is in NP, and therefore NP-complete.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] A discretized version of the problem with distances rounded to integers is NP-complete.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] With rational coordinates and the actual Euclidean metric, Euclidean TSP is known to be in the Counting Hierarchy, a subclass of PSPACE.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] With arbitrary real coordinates, Euclidean TSP cannot be in such classes, since there are uncountably many possible inputs.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Despite these complications, Euclidean TSP is much easier than the general metric case for approximation.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, the minimum spanning tree of the graph associated with an instance of the Euclidean TSP is a Euclidean minimum spanning tree, and so can be computed in expected *O*(*n* log *n*) time for *n* points (considerably less than the number of edges).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This enables the simple 2-approximation algorithm for TSP with triangle inequality above to operate more quickly.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] time; this is called a polynomial-time approximation scheme (PTAS).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Mitchell were awarded the Gödel Prize in 2010 for their concurrent discovery of a PTAS for the Euclidean TSP.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In practice, simpler heuristics with weaker guarantees continue to be used.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In most cases, the distance between two nodes in the TSP network is the same in both directions.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The case where the distance from *A* to *B* is not equal to the distance from *B* to *A* is called asymmetric TSP.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] A practical application of an asymmetric TSP is route optimization using street-level routing (which is made asymmetric by one-way streets, slip-roads, motorways, etc.).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The stacker crane problem can be viewed as a special case of the asymmetric TSP.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In this problem, the input consists of ordered pairs of points in a metric space, which must be visited consecutively in order by the tour.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] These pairs of points can be viewed as the nodes of an asymmetric TSP, with asymmetric distances reflecting the combined cost of traveling from the first point of a pair to its second and then from the second point of a pair to the first point of the next pair.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Solving an asymmetric TSP graph can be somewhat complex.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The following is a 3×3 matrix containing all possible path weights between the nodes *A*, *B* and *C*.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] One option is to turn an asymmetric matrix of size *N* into a symmetric matrix of size 2*N*.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] To double the size, each of the nodes in the graph is duplicated, creating a second *ghost node*, linked to the original node with a "ghost" edge of very low (possibly negative) weight, here denoted −*w*.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] (Alternatively, the ghost edges have weight 0, and weight w is added to all other edges.) The original 3×3 matrix shown above is visible in the bottom left and the transpose of the original in the top-right.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Both copies of the matrix have had their diagonals replaced by the low-cost hop paths, represented by −*w*.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In the new graph, no edge directly links original nodes and no edge directly links ghost nodes.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The weight −*w* of the "ghost" edges linking the ghost nodes to the corresponding original nodes must be low enough to ensure that all ghost edges must belong to any optimal symmetric TSP solution on the new graph (*w* = 0 is not always low enough).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] There is an analogous problem in geometric measure theory which asks the following: under what conditions may a subset *E* of Euclidean space be contained in a rectifiable curve (that is, when is there a curve with finite length that visits every point in *E*)?
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This problem is known as the analyst's travelling salesman problem.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Suppose $X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are n independent random variables with uniform distribution in the square $[0,1]^{2}$ , and let $L_{n}^{\ast }$ be the shortest path length (i.e.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] TSP solution) for this set of points, according to the usual Euclidean distance.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] where $\beta$ is a positive constant that is not known explicitly.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Since $L_{n}^{*}\leq 2{\sqrt {n}}+2$ (see below), it follows from bounded convergence theorem that $\beta =\lim _{n\to \infty }\mathbb {E} [L_{n}^{*}]/{\sqrt {n}}$ , hence lower and upper bounds on $\beta$ follow from bounds on $\mathbb {E} [L_{n}^{*}]$ .
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The almost-sure limit ${\frac {L_{n}^{*}}{\sqrt {n}}}\rightarrow \beta$ as $n\to \infty$ may not exist if the independent locations $X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are replaced with observations from a stationary ergodic process with uniform marginals.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Held and Karp gave a polynomial-time algorithm that provides numerical lower bounds for $L_{n}^{*}$ , and thus for $\beta (\simeq L_{n}^{*}/{\sqrt {n}})$ , which seem to be good up to more or less 1%.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] where 0.522 comes from the points near the square boundary which have fewer neighbours, and Christine L.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The problem has been shown to be NP-hard (more precisely, it is complete for the complexity class FPNP; see function problem), and the decision problem version ("given the costs and a number *x*, decide whether there is a round-trip route cheaper than *x*") is NP-complete.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The bottleneck travelling salesman problem is also NP-hard.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The problem remains NP-hard even for the case when the cities are in the plane with Euclidean distances, as well as in a number of other restrictive cases.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Removing the condition of visiting each city "only once" does not remove the NP-hardness, since in the planar case there is an optimal tour that visits each city only once (otherwise, by the triangle inequality, a shortcut that skips a repeated visit would not increase the tour length).
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In the general case, finding a shortest travelling salesman tour is NPO-complete.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distance measure is a metric (and thus symmetric), the problem becomes APX-complete, and the algorithm of Christofides and Serdyukov approximates it within 1.5.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distances are restricted to 1 and 2 (but still are a metric), then the approximation ratio becomes 8/7.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In the asymmetric case with triangle inequality, in 2018, a constant factor approximation was developed by Svensson, Tarnawski, and Végh.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] An algorithm by Vera Traub and Jens Vygen achieves a performance ratio of $22+\varepsilon$ .
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This factor was further improved to $17+\varepsilon$ .
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The best known inapproximability bound is 75/74.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The corresponding maximization problem of finding the *longest* travelling salesman tour is approximable within 63/38.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distance function is symmetric, then the longest tour can be approximated within 4/3 by a deterministic algorithm and within $(33+\varepsilon )/25$ by a randomized algorithm.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP, in particular the Euclidean variant of the problem, has attracted the attention of researchers in cognitive psychology.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] It has been observed that humans are able to produce near-optimal solutions quickly, in a close-to-linear fashion, with performance that ranges from 1% less efficient, for graphs with 10–20 nodes, to 11% less efficient for graphs with 120 nodes.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The apparent ease with which humans accurately generate near-optimal solutions to the problem has led researchers to hypothesize that humans use one or more heuristics, with the two most popular theories arguably being the convex-hull hypothesis and the crossing-avoidance heuristic.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] However, additional evidence suggests that human performance is quite varied, and individual differences as well as graph geometry appear to affect performance in the task.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Nevertheless, results suggest that computer performance on the TSP may be improved by understanding and emulating the methods used by humans for these problems, and have also led to new insights into the mechanisms of human thought.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The first issue of the *Journal of Problem Solving* was devoted to the topic of human performance on TSP, and a 2011 review listed dozens of papers on the subject.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In the first experiment, pigeons were placed in the corner of a lab room and allowed to fly to nearby feeders containing peas.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] The researchers found that pigeons largely used proximity to determine which feeder they would select next.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] In the second experiment, the feeders were arranged in such a way that flying to the nearest feeder at every opportunity would be largely inefficient if the pigeons needed to visit every feeder.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] This suggests non-primates may possess a relatively sophisticated spatial cognitive ability.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Humans are not the only species to show excellent efficiency.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, when presented with a spatial configuration of food sources, the amoeboid *Physarum polycephalum* adapts its morphology to create an efficient path between the food sources, which can also be viewed as an approximate solution to TSP.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Similarly, honey bees and bumblebees have been shown to be very adept at maximising efficiency to a very high degree of accuracy when collecting nectar and pollen by using collective intelligence.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] For benchmarking of TSP algorithms, TSPLIB is a library of sample instances of the TSP and related problems.
[src:christofides-tsp/travelling-salesman-problem] Many of them are lists of actual cities and layouts of actual printed circuits.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] In mathematics, the **triangle inequality** states that for any triangle, the sum of the lengths of any two sides must be greater than or equal to the length of the remaining side.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] This statement permits the inclusion of degenerate triangles, but some authors, especially those writing about elementary geometry, will exclude this possibility, thus leaving out the possibility of equality.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] with equality only in the degenerate case of a triangle with zero area.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] where the length of the third side has been replaced by the length of the vector sum **u** + **v**.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] When **u** and **v** are real numbers, they can be viewed as vectors in $\mathbb {R} ^{1}$ , and the triangle inequality expresses a relationship between absolute values.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] In Euclidean geometry, for right triangles the triangle inequality is a consequence of the Pythagorean theorem, and for general triangles, a consequence of the law of cosines, although it may be proved without these theorems.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The inequality can be viewed intuitively in either $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ or $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The figure at the right shows three examples beginning with clear inequality (top) and approaching equality (bottom).
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] In the Euclidean case, equality occurs only if the triangle has a 180° angle and two 0° angles, making the three vertices collinear, as shown in the bottom example.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Thus, in Euclidean geometry, the shortest distance between two points is a straight line.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The triangle inequality is a *defining property* of norms and measures of distance.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] This property must be established as a theorem for any function proposed for such purposes for each particular space: for example, spaces such as the real numbers, Euclidean spaces, the Lp spaces (*p* ≥ 1), and inner product spaces.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Euclid proved the triangle inequality for distances in plane geometry using the construction in the figure.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Beginning with triangle ABC, an isosceles triangle is constructed with one side taken as BC and the other equal leg BD along the extension of side AB.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] It then is argued that angle β has larger measure than angle α, so side AD is longer than side AC.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] so the sum of the lengths of sides AB and BC is larger than the length of AC.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] This proof appears in Euclid's Elements, Book I, Proposition 20.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] and thus that the longest side length is less than the semiperimeter.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] A mathematically equivalent formulation is that the area of a triangle with sides *a*, *b*, *c* must be a real number greater than zero.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] In terms of either area expression, the triangle inequality imposed on all sides is equivalent to the condition that the expression under the square root sign be real and greater than zero (so the area expression is real and greater than zero).
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] In the case of right triangles, the triangle inequality specializes to the statement that the hypotenuse is greater than either of the two sides and less than their sum.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The second part of this theorem is already established above for any side of any triangle.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The first part is established using the lower figure.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] In the figure, consider the right triangle ADC.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] An isosceles triangle ABC is constructed with equal sides *AB* = *AC*.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] That means side AD, which is opposite to angle α, is shorter than side AB, which is opposite to the larger angle β.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] A similar construction shows *AC* > *DC*, establishing the theorem.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] This theorem establishing inequalities is sharpened by Pythagoras' theorem to the equality that the square of the length of the hypotenuse equals the sum of the squares of the other two sides.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Consider a triangle whose sides are in an arithmetic progression and let the sides be *a*, *a* + *d*, *a* + 2*d*.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] When d is chosen such that *d* = *a*/3, it generates a right triangle that is always similar to the Pythagorean triple with sides 3, 4, 5.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Now consider a triangle whose sides are in a geometric progression and let the sides be *a*, *ar*, *ar*2.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The first inequality requires *a* > 0; consequently it can be divided through and eliminated.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] With *a* > 0, the middle inequality only requires *r* > 0.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The first of these quadratic inequalities requires r to range in the region beyond the value of the positive root of the quadratic equation *r*2 + *r* − 1 = 0, i.e.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] *r* > *φ* − 1 where φ is the golden ratio.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The second quadratic inequality requires r to range between 0 and the positive root of the quadratic equation *r*2 − *r* − 1 = 0, i.e.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] When r the common ratio is chosen such that *r* = √*φ* it generates a right triangle that is always similar to the Kepler triangle.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The triangle inequality can be extended by mathematical induction to arbitrary polygonal paths, showing that the total length of such a path is no less than the length of the straight line between its endpoints.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Consequently, the length of any polygon side is always less than the sum of the other polygon side lengths.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Consider a quadrilateral whose sides are in a geometric progression and let the sides be *a*, *ar*, *ar*2, *ar*3.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The left-hand side polynomials of these two inequalities have roots that are the tribonacci constant and its reciprocal.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Consequently, r is limited to the range 1/*t* < *r* < *t* where t is the tribonacci constant.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] This generalization can be used to prove that the shortest curve between two points in Euclidean geometry is a straight line.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] No polygonal path between two points is shorter than the line between them.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] This implies that no curve can have an arc length less than the distance between its endpoints.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] By definition, the arc length of a curve is the least upper bound of the lengths of all polygonal approximations of the curve.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The result for polygonal paths shows that the straight line between the endpoints is the shortest of all the polygonal approximations.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Because the arc length of the curve is greater than or equal to the length of every polygonal approximation, the curve itself cannot be shorter than the straight line path.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] In either case, if the side lengths are a, b, c we can attempt to place a triangle in the Euclidean plane as shown in the diagram.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] We need to prove that there exists a real number h consistent with the values a, b, and c, in which case this triangle exists.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] By the Pythagorean theorem we have *b*2 = *h*2 + *d*2 and *a*2 = *h*2 + (*c* − *d*)2 according to the figure at the right.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] For the height of the triangle we have that *h*2 = *b*2 − *d*2.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] which holds if the triangle inequality is satisfied for all sides.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Therefore, there does exist a real number h consistent with the sides $a,b,c$ , and the triangle exists.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] If each triangle inequality holds strictly, $h>0$ and the triangle is non-degenerate (has positive area); but if one of the inequalities holds with equality, so $h=0$ , the triangle is degenerate.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The area of a triangular face of a tetrahedron is less than or equal to the sum of the areas of the other three triangular faces.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] More generally, in Euclidean space the hypervolume of an (*n* − 1)-facet of an n-simplex is less than or equal to the sum of the hypervolumes of the other n facets.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Much as the triangle inequality generalizes to a polygon inequality, the inequality for a simplex of any dimension generalizes to a polytope of any dimension: the hypervolume of any facet of a polytope is less than or equal to the sum of the hypervolumes of the remaining facets.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] In some cases the tetrahedral inequality is stronger than several applications of the triangle inequality.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] That is, the norm of the sum of two vectors is at most as large as the sum of the norms of the two vectors.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] This is also referred to as subadditivity.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] For any proposed function to behave as a norm, it must satisfy this requirement.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] This property characterizes strictly convex normed spaces such as the ℓp spaces with 1 < *p* < ∞.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] However, there are normed spaces in which this is not true.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] For instance, consider the plane with the *ℓ*1 norm (the Manhattan distance) and denote **u** = (1, 0) and **v** = (0, 1).
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The *absolute value* is a norm for the real line; as required, the absolute value satisfies the triangle inequality for any real numbers u and v.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The triangle inequality is useful in mathematical analysis for determining the best upper estimate on the size of the sum of two numbers, in terms of the sizes of the individual numbers.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The *taxicab norm* or 1-norm is one generalization absolute value to higher dimensions.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The *Euclidean norm* or 2-norm defines the length of translation vectors in an n-dimensional Euclidean space in terms of a Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The *inner product* is norm in any inner product space, a generalization of Euclidean vector spaces including infinite-dimensional examples.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The Cauchy–Schwarz inequality turns into an equality if and only if u and v are linearly dependent.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The inequality $\langle u,v\rangle +\langle v,u\rangle \leq 2\left|\left\langle u,v\right\rangle \right|$ turns into an equality for linearly dependent u and v if and only if one of the vectors u or v is a *nonnegative* scalar of the other.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Taking the square root of the final result gives the triangle inequality.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The p-norm is a generalization of taxicab and Euclidean norms, using an arbitrary positive integer exponent, $\|v\|_{p}={\bigl (}|v_{1}|^{p}+|v_{2}|^{p}+\dotsb +|v_{n}|^{p}{\bigr )}^{1/p},$ where the vi are the components of vector v.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] Except for the case *p* = 2, the p-norm is *not* an inner product norm, because it does not satisfy the parallelogram law.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The triangle inequality for general values of p is called Minkowski's inequality.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] That is, the distance from A to C is at most as large as the sum of the distance from A to B and the distance from B to C.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The triangle inequality is responsible for most of the interesting structure on a metric space, namely, convergence.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] This is because the remaining requirements for a metric are rather simplistic in comparison.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] so that the sequence {*xn*} is a Cauchy sequence, by definition.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] This version of the triangle inequality reduces to the one stated above in case of normed vector spaces where a metric is induced via $d(u,v):=\|u-v\|,$ with *u* − *v* being the vector pointing from point v to u.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The **reverse triangle inequality** is an equivalent alternative formulation of the triangle inequality that gives lower bounds instead of upper bounds.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The Minkowski space metric $\eta _{\mu \nu }$ is not positive-definite, which means that $\|u\|^{2}=\eta _{\mu \nu }u^{\mu }u^{\nu }$ can have either sign or vanish, even if the vector u is non-zero.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] A physical example of this inequality is the twin paradox in special relativity.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The same reversed form of the inequality holds if both vectors lie in the past light cone, and if one or both are null vectors.
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] The result holds in $n+1$ dimensions for any $n\geq 1$ .
[src:christofides-tsp/triangle-inequality] If the plane defined by u and v is space-like (and therefore a Euclidean subspace) then the usual triangle inequality holds.
